{"cursor":"22537","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Pseudobulbar affect' ('PBA'), 'emotional lability', 'labile affect' or\n'emotional incontinence' refers to a neurologic disorder characterized by\ninvoluntary crying or uncontrollable episodes of crying and/or laughing, or\nother emotional displays. PBA occurs secondary to neurologic disease\nor brain injury. Patients may find themselves crying uncontrollably at something\nthat is only moderately sad, being unable to stop themselves for several\nminutes. Episodes may also be mood-incongruent: a patient might laugh\nuncontrollably when angry or frustrated, for example.\n","linknr":348,"url":"Labile_affect","recorded":1362889827,"links":15,"instances":["psychology"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Neurological disorders"],"headings":["Terminology","Clinical presentation","Background and current understanding","Other effects","Prevalence of PBA symptoms","Treatment","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/PBA_is_not_depression.png/220px-PBA_is_not_depression.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["affect","psychology"]],"members":["affect"],"related":["Neurologic_disorder","Brain_injury","Emotional_response","ELISA","Western_Blot","Alzheimer's","Prefrontal_cortex","Neural_networks","Traumatic_brain_injury","Stroke","Dementias","Alzheimer's_disease","Multiple_sclerosis","Amyotrophic_lateral_sclerosis","Parkinson's_disease","Brain_tumors","Wilsonâ€™s_disease","Pseudobulbar_palsy","Encephalitis","Epilepsy","Central_pontine_myelinolysis","Olivopontinocerebellar_atrophy","Lipid_storage_diseases","Toxicity","Nitrous_oxide","Insecticides","Angelman_syndrome","Learning_disability","Coping_skill","Ant